[1] Global as of 30 Mar 2022 - GPEI/WHO cVDPV2 (AFP DR Congo, Nigeria, Yemen; ES Egypt)
Date: Thu 31 Mar 2022
Source: Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI)/World Health Organization (WHO) [edited]
https://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/this-week/


Poliovirus weekly update as of 30 Mar 2022, World Health Organization
---------------------------------------------------------------------
New wild poliovirus isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 0
Environment: 0
Others: 0

New cVDPV isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 25
Environment: 4
Others: 1

Headlines
---------
- On 21 Mar 2022, the Federal Government of Somalia, World Health Organization (WHO) and members of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI) recommitted to stopping the ongoing outbreak of circulating poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) in Somalia at a 3-day meeting convened in Nairobi, Kenya. Details of the summit are available at https://polioeradication.org/news-post/somalia-call-to-action-summit-for-polio/.

- Revised containment guidance (GAPIII) available for public consultation:
On recommendation from the Containment Advisory Group (CAG), and through wide engagement of stakeholders, WHO's Global Action Plan for Poliovirus Containment (GAPIII, 2015) has been revised. Following a period of critical review by the CAG, the document draft is now available for public consultation until 1 May 2022. Revisions to the guidance have been made based on CAG recommendations, review of relevant bio-risk management documents to determine alignment, scientific evidence and solicited stakeholder comments on various sections. WHO encourages feedback from containment stakeholders. For queries, please email: <containment@who.int>. [Strategy document available linking through https://polioeradication.org/polio-today/preparing-for-a-polio-free-world/containment/containment-resources/. - Mod.MPP]

Summary of new polioviruses this week:
- DR Congo: 6 cVDPV2 cases
- Egypt: 2 cVDPV2 positive environmental samples
- Nigeria: 3 cVDPV2 cases and 2 positive environmental samples
- Yemen: 16 cVDPV2 cases

Afghanistan
- No new WPV1 or cVDPV2 viruses were reported this week. There is 1 WPV1 case reported in 2022 and 4 in 2021. The total number of cVDPV2 cases remains 43.

Pakistan
- No new WPV1 or cVDPV2 viruses were reported this week. The total number of WPV1 cases in 2021 remains 1. The total number of cVDPV2 cases remains 8.

Benin
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 3 cases reported in 2021.

Burkina Faso
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.

Cameroon
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 3 cases reported in 2021.

Central African Republic
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are no cases reported in 2021.

Chad
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are no cases reported in 2021.

Congo (Republic of)
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.

CÃ´te d'Ivoire
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are no reported cases in 2021.

Djibouti
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental samples were reported this week. There are 5 positive environmental samples reported in the country, linked to the virus circulating in Yemen.

Democratic Republic of the Congo (DR Congo)
- 6 cases of cVDPV2 were reported in Maniema, bringing the number of 2022 cases to 9. There are 28 cases from 2021.

Egypt
- 2 cVDPV2 positive environmental samples were reported in Qena. There are 13 positive samples reported in 2021.
- A national immunization campaign is being held this week with bivalent OPV.
- An internal surveillance review is scheduled for May [2022], as part of preparations for the expected Outbreak Response Assessment.

Ethiopia
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 10 cases reported in 2021.

Gambia
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental samples were reported this week. There are 9 positive samples reported in 2021.

Guinea
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 6 cases in 2021.

Guinea-Bissau
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 3 cases in the country which are linked to the Jigawa outbreak in Nigeria in 2021.

Israel
- No case of cVDPV3 was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in the country.

Liberia
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 3 cVDPV2 cases in the country in 2021.

Madagascar
- No case of cVDPV1 was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains 13. There is 1 case in 2022.

Malawi
- No case of WPV1 was reported this week. Last month [February 2022], the country reported the 1st WPV1 case in the continent since 2016.
- Last week, multi-country outbreak responses were conducted, in Malawi and neighbouring countries, in response to the recently-detected WPV1 in the country.
- The activity aimed to reach more than 9.2 million children across Malawi, Tanzania, Zambia and Mozambique over the next week. It was the 1st of a series of multi-country, emergency outbreak response activities to be held in the subregion.
- Initial monitoring in the country indicates upwards of 94% of the target population was successfully reached during the campaign.
- GPEI partners were supporting local health authorities in their efforts, in particular also through local Rotarians across the country.
- UNICEF supported authorities in communications and social mobilization activities, including through organization of media tours, community engagement meetings, public service announcements and other activities.
- Commenting about these outbreak response activities, WHO Regional Director for Africa, Dr Matshidiso Moeti, said: "In support of Malawi and its neighbours, we are acting fast to halt this outbreak and extinguish the threat through effective vaccinations. The African region has already defeated wild poliovirus due to a monumental effort by countries. We have the know-how and are tirelessly working to ensure that every child lives and thrives in a continent free of polio."
- In response to confirmation of the WPV1 outbreak in the country, the Government of Malawi declared the outbreak a national public health emergency and activated the emergency operations centre to coordinate outbreak response. Global and regional support from the GPEI Rapid Response Team are in-country to support planning, implementing and monitoring of response.
- The response plan includes at least 4 large-scale outbreak response campaigns with bivalent OPV.
- In terms of next steps: the country aims to conduct a complete analysis of this campaign, and begin planning for the next multi-country activity, including by implementing any corrective measures as necessary/lessons learned from the 1st round.

Mauritania
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 7 positive samples linked to the Jigawa outbreak in 2021.

Mozambique
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.
- In response to the confirmed cVDPV2 outbreak in the country, the Minister of Health declared the outbreak to be a national public health emergency in February [2022].
- Last week, Mozambique participated in the 1st of a series of multi-country outbreak response campaigns, in response to detection of WPV1 in neighbouring Malawi.
- The country aimed to reach 4.3 million children. The campaign was officially launched by the Honourable Minister of Health, Professor Dr Armindo Tiago, urging to "quickly vaccinate all children under 5 years of age, as polio is a serious public health concern and can be easily transmitted among unvaccinated children."
- A national emergency operations centre had been established to coordinate the outbreak response activities. Coordination across all levels of operations focused on planning, monitoring, health worker training, vaccine supply, and extensive communications and social mobilization to [ensure] high levels of community engagement.

Niger
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 17 cases reported in 2021.

Nigeria
- 3 cases of cVDPV2 were reported, 2 in Bauchi and 1 in Gombe, bringing the number of 2022 cases to 8. The number of 2021 cases remains 415.
- 2 positive environmental samples were reported in Sokoto.
- The 38th Meeting of the Expert Review Committee (ERC) on Polio Eradication and Routine Immunization convened in Abuja on 14-15 Mar 2022. The group reviewed the latest poliovirus epidemiology in the country and put forward key recommendations.
- The group highlighted the need to urgently address the resurgence of cVDPV2 in the country since March 2021, noting that outbreak response is taking place under challenging circumstances of increasing insecurity in some areas, COVID-19 pandemic and other outbreak response efforts.
- The ERC underscored the need for increased quality outbreak response through advocacy at all levels of government, particularly at State and Local Government Area (LGA) levels, in fully implemented planned, large-scale campaigns (nOPV2 and also phased fIPV campaigns).
- The group also noted the need to minimize the risk of WPV1 re-introduction, particularly given detection of this strain this year [2022] in Malawi.

Senegal
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 17 cases reported in 2021.

Sierra Leone
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 5 cases reported in 2021.

Somalia
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in 2022 and 1 case in 2021.
- Last week, a high-level summit of stakeholders was held to take urgent action to end ongoing cVDPV2 outbreak and protect country from WPV re-infection.
- The Federal Government of Somalia and members of the GPEI recommitted to the effort at this high-level delegate meeting convened by HE Fawziya Abikar Nur, Federal Minister of Health and Human Services.
- The meeting affirmed their commitment to the Somalia Polio Eradication Action Plan, which focuses efforts and resources towards boosting population immunity, making concerted efforts to reach high-risk populations -- including inaccessible and nomadic communities and internally displaced persons -- to strengthen their immunity, enhancing the search for poliovirus circulation, and strengthening coordination among all stakeholders. Some of the strategies that will be deployed include intensifying efforts to offer 5 opportunities for vaccination against polio in 2022, providing routine childhood immunization in high-risk locations, where children have missed out on vaccinations, and strengthening community engagement.
- "In the midst of the ongoing drought, and while recovering from the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic, our stakeholders must not forget how important it is to contain the ongoing poliovirus outbreak so that it does not spread any further and does not affect any more children's lives," said HE Fawziya Abikar Nur. "On this occasion, I would like to extend my sincere gratitude to all our partners, and donors, for the immense efforts they have put into shielding millions of Somali children from polio over the years."
- Efforts are continuing to strengthen both immunity levels and surveillance sensitivity in the country. This week, for example, a technical assessment and support mission in Somaliland took place to strengthen both surveillance for AFP and measles.

South Sudan
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 9 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2021.

Tajikistan
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 32 cases reported in 2021.

Uganda
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 2 positive samples linked to the N'Djamena outbreak in Chad reported in 2021.

Ukraine
- No case of cVDPV2 was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.
- The GPEI is extremely concerned about the unfolding effects of the current crisis in Ukraine on the country's health system. A functioning health system must be kept neutral and protected from all political or security issues affecting countries, to ensure that people have continued access to critical and essential care.
- A national supplemental polio immunization campaign targeting nearly 140 000 children throughout Ukraine who had not been vaccinated against polio began on 1 Feb 2022, but is currently paused, as health authorities have shifted focus towards emergency services. Surveillance to detect and report new cases of polio is also disrupted, increasing the risk of undetected spread of the disease among vulnerable populations. The GPEI is working to urgently develop contingency plans to support Ukraine and prevent further spread of polio. While the cold winter climate of Ukraine is not conducive to polio transmission, undetected residual transmission cannot be ruled out, particularly as the surveillance system has been disrupted.
- The GPEI has a long history of working in a variety of complex environments and will continue to adapt its operations to the reality on the ground, to the degree possible, without compromising on the safety and security of health workers. At the same time, immunization and surveillance is being assessed in neighbouring countries, to minimize the risk and consequences of any potential infectious disease emergence/spread resulting from the current large-scale population movements. It is critical that necessary resources are mobilized and made available to assist with the humanitarian needs, including relief, disease response/prevention efforts both in Ukraine and in neighbouring countries.
- Immunization and surveillance is being assessed in neighbouring countries to minimize the risk and consequences of any potential infectious disease emergence/spread resulting from large-scale population movements.
- The GPEI is strengthening synergies with broader immunization needs for displaced persons, including polio vaccines in the package of health interventions and using polio surveillance to help detect other vaccine-preventable diseases.
- The GPEI is assessing the availability of IPV and measles vaccines in key areas; assessing cold chain capacity and potential impact on it due to electricity cuts; providing communication support for demand generation for immunization; and supporting proactive AFP and environmental surveillance in all IDP sites.
- In border areas, operational support is provided to set up mobile vaccination teams and ensuring safe and efficient transport and temporary storage of vaccines.
- In neighbouring countries (Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia, Hungary), support is focusing on strengthening surveillance (AFP and environmental); registration of children; procurement of vaccines; increased communication to generate vaccine demand; and strengthening immunization in camps and refugee settlements.

Yemen
- 16 cases of cVDPV2 were reported, 1 each in Aden, Aldhale and Dhamar; 2 each in Alhudaidah and Aljawf; and 3 each in Amran, Marib and Saadah, bringing the number of 2021 cVDPV2 cases to 32 while number of cVDPV1 cases remains 3.
- Efforts are continuing to strengthen surveillance, particularly in high-risk areas, but security and logistical challenges continue to slow the movement of samples to laboratories outside of the country.

Officially reported WPV1 and cVDPV cases as of 29 Mar 2022
Wild poliovirus (WPV)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2022: 1 (compared with 2 for the same period in 2021)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2021: 6

Circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus (cVDPV) cases
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2022: 20 (compared with 43 for the same period in 2021)
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2021: 659

